    {
      "content": {
        "parts": [
          {
            "text": "{\n  \"verdict\": \"NEEDS_REVISION\",\n  \"summary\": \"The plan is well-structured and correctly identifies the critical need to secure the API key, but it introduces a new centralized proxy without sufficient security, input validation, or consideration for its role as a single point of failure.\",\n  \"issues\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"description\": \"The shared AI proxy in App 1's backend has no authentication or authorization mechanism. As designed, any application or script on the local network can call the `/api/ai/*` endpoints, consuming expensive API quota and potentially injecting malicious data.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Implement a simple shared secret authentication method. The server should require an `X-API-Key` header on all proxy requests. Store this secret key in the server's `process.env` and in the `.env` files of App 2 and App 3 (e.g., `VITE_AI_PROXY_KEY`). The server must validate this key on every incoming request.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"major\",\n      \"description\": \"The backend plan specifies Zod validation for Gemini's *output* but omits validation for the *input* coming from the client apps. This exposes the backend to malformed requests, which could cause unexpected errors, crashes, or wasted API calls with invalid data.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Apply Zod validation to the request bodies of all `POST /api/ai/*` routes in `server/routes/gemini.ts`. Reject any request that does not conform to the expected schema with a `400 Bad Request` status code before it is sent to the Gemini API.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"major\",\n      \"description\": \"The architecture introduces a single point of failure (SPOF). If App 1's Node.js server crashes or fails to start, all AI features for all three applications will be completely non-functional, even the local fallbacks in Apps 2 and 3 might not be triggered correctly depending on the client implementation.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"For the competition, this risk is acceptable but must be acknowledged. Add a step to the pre-demo checklist to explicitly verify the App 1 server is running and responsive. For a production system, a dedicated, independently deployable microservice would be required instead of embedding the proxy in one of the apps.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"minor\",\n      \"description\": \"The error handling contract focuses on returning errors to the client but lacks any server-side logging. During the demo, if the proxy experiences timeouts or Zod validation failures, it will be difficult to debug the root cause in real-time without any server logs.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"In the `catch` blocks and validation failure paths on the App 1 server, add `console.error` or a more robust logger to record the specific error (e.g., 'Gemini timeout', 'Zod validation failed', 'Invalid API key') along with a timestamp before returning the `{error, fallback: true}` response.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"minor\",\n      \"description\": \"The plan mentions `vitest` will be run, but it does not specify what tests should be written for the new, critical functionality. The client-side logic for catching proxy errors and activating local fallbacks is a key failure mode that needs to be explicitly tested.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a requirement to write specific unit tests for the new AI client services in each app. These tests must mock the proxy fetch call to verify two scenarios: 1) successful API response is processed correctly, and 2) a thrown error (e.g., network failure, 500 status) correctly triggers the local fallback logic.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"info\",\n      \"description\": \"The client-side timeout (6 seconds) is shorter than the server-side timeout (8 seconds), which is correct. However, this creates a 2-second window where the server might still be processing a request (and incurring an API cost) that the client has already abandoned. This can lead to orphaned requests and wasted resources.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"The server should listen for the client closing the connection. In Express.js, this can be done by listening to the `req.on('close', ...)` event and using the `AbortController` to cancel the in-flight Gemini API request if the client disconnects.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"info\",\n      \"description\": \"The detailed plan for the App 3 SVG Campus Map does not include any accessibility considerations. Visually impaired users relying on screen readers will not be able to understand the map's layout or risk status.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Incorporate basic SVG accessibility features. Add a `\u003ctitle\u003e` element to the main `\u003csvg\u003e` tag describing the map. For each major zone (`\u003cg\u003e` element), include a `\u003ctitle\u003e` or `aria-label` attribute describing the location and its current risk level (e.g., '圖書館 - 低風險').\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"
          }
        ],
        "role": "model"
      },
